ld literary system? The Worlding of Arabic Literature argues that an ethical translation of a work of Arabic literature is one that transmits the literariness of the source text by engaging new populations of readers via a range of embodied and sensory effects. The book proposes that when translation is conceived of not as an exchange of semantic content but as a process of converting the affective forms of one language into those of another, previously unrecognized modalities of worldliness open up to the source text.In dialogue with a rich corpus of Arabic aesthetic and linguistic theory as well as contemporary scholarship in affect theory, translation theory, postcolonial theory, and world literature studies, this book offers a timely and provocative investigation of how an important literary tradition enters the world literary system.The Worlding of Arabic Literature: Language, Affect, and the Ethics of Translatability is available from the publisher on an open-access basis.  afunded by TOME: Toward an Open Monograph Ecosystem  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aArabic literaturevTranslations into EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aArabic literaturexAppreciation. 0aTranslating and interpretingxMoral and ethical aspects. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aMiddle Eastern Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh  aArabic literature.  aArabic-to-English translation.  aaesthetics.  aaffect.  aethics.  aliterariness.  aliterary prizes.  areading.  atranslation.  aworld literature.2 aTOME: Toward an Open Monograph Ecosystemefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Engli